##Individual Plots of Your Names popularity over time

###Rachael

The regular expression I used to match the variations of my name in the data set was ^R[eay]+ch[ae]+l$.

I was born in the year 1998. According to the graph, this looks like the end of the peak popularity for the name Rachael and its variations. In 1998, Rachael and its variations had a popularity proportion of about 0.0095. After the year 2000, the graph shows a sharp decline in the popularity of my name, approaching a popularity proportion of about 0.001. Thus, my name is significantly less popular now than it was when I was born.

The graph shows a strong relationship between names that start with Rac and Rachael, indicating that it is rare for a name to start with the letters Rac and not end up being Rachael or a variation. This is corroborated by observation in the data set. Due to this relationship, names that start with Rac and the name Rachael are approximately equal in popularity now, according to the graph.

###Manasi

library(tidyverse) library(babynames) baby <- babynames::babynames

baby1 <- baby %>% filter(str_detect(name, ^Man)) %>% group_by(year) %>% mutate(totalprop = sum(prop))

baby2 <- baby %>% filter(str_detect(name, ^Man[a]+s[ei]$)) %>% group_by(year) %>% mutate(totalprop = sum(prop))

ggplot() + geom_line(data = baby1, mapping = aes(x= year, y=totalprop, color = Man)) + geom_line(data = baby2, mapping = aes(x=year, y= totalprop, color = Manasi/variations)) + labs(title = Popularity of names that start with Man and the name Manasi, x = Year, y = Popularity Proportion, color = Matches with Name)

The regular expression I used to match the variations of my name in the data set was ^R[eay]+ch[ae]+l$. The peak of names starting with Man is in the 1970s. I was born in 2000. In 2000, they were at a middle proportion. After the 1970s, the plot shows a sharp decline in the popularity its significantly less popular now than it was when I was born. There arent many Manasis or variations because it is not as common of a name in India so there isnt much of a correlation with Man vs Manasi.

1973:

## 5  1973 F     Rachal     24 0.0000154
## 6  1973 F     Raechel    17 0.0000109
## [1] 0.00471611

Thus, there is a 0.0047 chance that a baby girl born in 1973 will be named Ariel, Rachel, or variations.

1988:

## [1] 0.01064194

Thus, there is a 0.011 chance of female being named Ariel, Rachel, or their variations in 1988.

1990:

## [1] 0.01214041

Thus, there is a 0.012 chance of a girl being named Ariel, Rachel, or a variation on those names in 1990.

2017:

## [1] 0.00262041

Therefore, there is a 0.0026 chance of a baby girl being named Rachel, Ariel, or a variation in 2017.

##The Little Mermaid Effect

###What was the change in proportion in female Ariel baby names? Considering all the changes in female names starting with a vowel from 1988 to 1990, what percentile is the change in Ariel names?

## # A tibble: 6 x 10
##   year.x sex.x name  n_1988 prop_1988 year.y sex.y n_1990 prop_1990
##    <dbl> <chr> <chr>  <int>     <dbl>  <dbl> <chr>  <int>     <dbl>
## 1   1988 F     Alys   7137  0.00371    1990 F      11262   0.00548
## 2   1988 F     Ariel    910  0.000473   1990 F       3606   0.00176
## 3   1988 F     Emily  15870  0.00825    1990 F      19363   0.00943
## 4   1988 F     Oliv   2138  0.00111    1990 F       4625   0.00225
## 5   1988 F     Alex   2902  0.00151    1990 F       5256   0.00256
## 6   1988 F     Abig   2374  0.00123    1990 F       3718   0.00181
## # ... with 1 more variable: change_prop <dbl>
## [1] 0.00178573

The change in proportion of of female baby names that are of Ariel-type spellings between 1988 and 1990 is +0.00178573. By filtering two tibbles for baby names that started with vowels in 1988 and 1990, respectively, and then by merging the two (removing an NA rows), I was able to create a new data frame in which, I could calculate changes in proportion for all the names. This was done using mutate and taking the difference in proportions of names. After sorting the tibble in ascending order my the change in proportion, it was possible to answer the latter of the two questions: what percentile is the change in Ariel names? The largest change in proportion between 1988 and 1990 was for the name Alyssa and had a change in proportion of +0.00177086. However, after adding up all the changes in proportion for the variations spellings of Ariel, we got a larger change in proportion. For this reason, the change in Ariel names is in the 100th percentile.

###Graphing the change in proportion

The plot above is a time series, which demonstrates the relative popularity of certain names in the babynames dataset. The years observed in particular were 1988-1990, which is related to the release of the movie The Little Mermaid. The blue line depicts the change in proportion of female names that begin with a vowel over this time period, whereas the red line shows the relatively change in proportion of Ariel and its variations. Because of the nature of the dataset, to see the changes more clearly, the popularity proportion of these names were standardized by multiplicative and logarithmic scaling. Thus, the change in popularity is standardized, and its clearly observed there is a stronger rise in popularity in the name Ariel over this time period.

From the plot above, its clear that the name Ariel and its variations rose in popularity in the throughout the years 1988 to 1990, as observed in this dataset. Looking at the base comparison, which is the female names which start with a vowel, its clear the popularity proportion remained nearly constant throughout the target years. Due to this constancy, the relative change in popularity of the name Ariel is significant, and substantively large. Therefore, its reasonable to conclude from this visualisation and analysis that The Little Mermaid did indeed have a relatively large effect on the popularity of the name Ariel, as reflected in this dataset.

###William

The first part of the lab tasked us with individually determining how the proportion of various ways of spelling our name changed with time. Additionally, how the proportion of names starting with the first three letters of our names changed over time. I chose to implement this manually as opposed to looking at the proportion column of the babynames tibble. I began by creating a tibble which was a filtered version of the babynames tibble based on those names that started with Wil. I then used parse_date to change the date column to type date. Then, I created another tibble which took the filtered tible based on the first three letters of my name, grouped them by year, and counted so that I could have a total number of names starting with Wil by year. I also needed a total number of names by year so that I could derive proportions so I created one. I then merged the tibbles of total number of names starting with Wil and total number of names by year based on the date key. With mutate, I created a prop_Wil column which was the proportion of names starting with Wil over time. I followed a similar logic and added a column of total number of William-type spellings into this aggregated tibble so that I could also come up with a proportion of total number of Williams by year. I used the regex: ^Will[iye]+am. After I had everything I needed in the same tibble, I used ggplot to show how the respective proportions changed over time. Because I was using to geom_line function calls, I ran into some difficultly figuring out how to label the key, howver, find a solution which can be viewed in my code implemented above. To end the individual section, I answered the respective questions. How popular is your name now compared to when you were born? To answer this question, I filtered my aggregated tibble by date twice, once for my birth year of 1997 and once for the most recent year in the data of 2017. I muliplied the prop_William column in both of the aforementioned filtered data frames by 100 to get the answers in a percent and reported them to show what the percentage change in proportion of William names was between 1997 and 2017. How popular is your name now relative to the other names that start with the same three letters? To answer this, I, like above, computed a percentage for the proportion of names starting with Will in 2017 and compared that with the percentage for the proportion of names speled like William in 2017.

For the group part, I contributed by answering the following questions. What was the change in proportion in female Ariel baby names? Considering all the changes in female names starting with a vowel from 1988 to 1990, what percentile is the change in Ariel names? To answer the first question, I began by creating a new tibble which filtered the babynames tibble for female names starting with vowels in 1988. I created another tibble which filtered for female names starting with vowels in 1990. I joined these two tibbles and dropped the NA values. Then, using the mutate function, I came up with a change in proportion column which was calculated by taking the difference between the proportion of a respective name in 1990 and the proportion of that same name in 1988. I arranged the tibble based on this newly created column in ascending order. Then, from this tibble, I created a new tibble which filtered for names that followed the appropriate regex. I summed the change in proportion columns of this new tibble to get the total change in proportion for Ariel-type spellings between 1988 and 1990. I got a value of 0.00178573. I then compared this value to the preceding tibble which sorted the change in proportion of female names starting with vowels between 1988 and 1990 by ascending order. The largest change in proporiton was 0.00177086 which was smaller than the previously computed value so I concluded that the change in Ariel names was in the 100th percentile.
